vectorData.altText:
Elevation and depression are movements up and down, respectively. They occur at the temporomandibular joint (TMJ) when we chew, and between the scapula and thorax when we shrug our shoulders.
Protraction and retraction are movements forward and backward, respectively. They occur at the TMJ when we jut our jaw outward and then pull it backward, and between the scapula and thorax when we row a boat     . 
Pronation and supination are special terms used to describe the rotation of the forearm around its long axis. Starting in anatomical position, rotation of the forearm such that the palm is facing backward is pronation. Rotation of the forearm such that the palm is facing forward is supination. Thus, in anatomical position, the forearm is supinated          . 
Opposition touches the pads of the thumb and a finger together. Reposition returns them to the anatomical position.
Lateral flexion or lateral bending is a movement specific to the vertebral column, in which we bend from side to side, as in sliding our hand down the lateral aspect of the leg     . 
Dorsiflexion and plantarflexion are movements specific to the talocrural (or ankle) joint, in which the foot is turned upward and downward, respectively. Plantarflexion of the talocrural joint permits you to point your toes     .
Eversion and inversion are movements specific to the foot, in which we turn the sole of the foot outward (as in toward a side wall) and inward (as in toward the other foot), respectively     .

The body is supine when lying on its back. The body is prone when lying on its front. Mnemonic: Starting in anatomical position, flex your elbow. Your palm is now facing the ceiling; it is supinated. How would you like to carry a bowl of soup? with your forearm supinated or pronated? “Soup-inated”, of course!
